Bobi Wine rejected the condition, saying other presidential candidates are in the field campaigning without signing the document.
Daily Monitor could not ascertain whether or not other presidential candidates signed the MoU.
“Justice Byabakama is a judge but he is the one who is flouting the law with impunity. We have written to him complaining about several things and he has continued to go silent about it. We cannot sign this MoU. We shall, however, reach out to the people anyway,” Mr Kyagulanyi told journalists in Kampala Tuesday.





Some of the districts in question are Kaliro, Pallisa, Kaberamaido, Kwania, Namutumba, Ngora, Bukedea, Kalaki, Amolatar, Serere, Buyende, Bugweri, Butebo and Dokolo.
In the MoU, all presidential candidates are required to hold peaceful campaigns and follow the Covid-19 guidelines from the Ministry of Health and EC guidelines on processions.
Also, candidates are not allowed to be in the same districts.
Bobi Wine said he had missed out on campaigning in these districts because police had blocked him from accessing these areas without a clear explanation.
EC spokesperson Paul Bukenya Tuesday reminded Bobi Wine that he had to comply with the set conditions before visiting the 16 districts.



